ings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Holtby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): habitational name from either of two places called Holtby in North Yorkshire, from the Old Norse personal name <i>Holti</i> + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Holby","meanings":["English (Essex): apparently a habitational name, possibly a variant of   Holtby  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Latham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lathom in Lancashire, or occasionally perhaps from Laytham in Yorkshire. The placenames mean ‘at the barns’, from <i>hlǫthum</i>, the dative plural form of Old Norse <i>hlatha</i> ‘barn, store house’."],"variants":[{"name":"Laden","meanings":["Probably a transferred use of the surname, a reduced and altered form of Irish and Scottish <i>McCadden</i>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Cadáin</i> ‘son of Cadán’."]},{"name":"Leathem","meanings":["Irish (northern): variant of   Latham  .","Irish: variant of   Lydon  ."]},{"name":"Leatham","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Latham  ."]},{"name":"Lathan","meanings":["Traditional name from a diminutive of <i>cath</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Lathem","meanings":["English: variant of   Latham  ."]},{"name":"Ledden","meanings":["English: variant of   Latham  .","Irish: variant of   Lydon  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":19,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":32,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":41,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan De Latham De Holtby was born about 1296, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England as the daughter of William Holtby. She married William Darell about 1317, in Sessay, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 14 November 1374, in Retreat, Suffolk, England, at the age of 79, and was buried in Retreat, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1296–14 November 1374":"umbes 1296–14. november 1374","1296–1374":"1296–1374","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1374":"1374","1296":"1296","14 November 1374":"14. november 1374","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","about 1319":"umbes 1319","about 1317":"umbes 1317","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1319":"1319","about 1296":"umbes 1296","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Sessay, Yorkshire, England":"Sessay, Yorkshire, England","Retreat, Suffolk, England":"Retreat, Suffolk, England","Gipton, Yorkshire, Eng